***Diff in metals and non metals:
| **Sr. No.** | **Property**                        | **Metals**                                | **Non-Metals**                           |
| ----------- | ----------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------- |
| 1           | **Appearance**                      | Lustrous (shiny)                          | Dull, not shiny                          |
| 2           | **Malleability**                    | Malleable (can be hammered into sheets)   | Brittle, breaks on hammering             |
| 3           | **Ductility**                       | Ductile (can be drawn into wires)         | Non-ductile                              |
| 4           | **Conductivity**                    | Good conductors of heat and electricity   | Poor conductors (insulators)             |
| 5           | **Density**                         | Usually high                              | Usually low                              |
| 6           | **Melting & Boiling Point**         | High                                      | Low                                      |
| 7           | **Tendency to Lose/Gain Electrons** | Lose electrons to form cations (+ve ions) | Gain electrons to form anions (-ve ions) |
| 8           | **State at Room Temp**              | Mostly solid (except mercury)             | Solid, liquid, or gas                    |
| 9           | **Strength**                        | Strong and hard                           | Weak and soft                            |
| 10          | **Reaction with Acids**             | Reacts with acids to produce hydrogen gas | Usually does not react with acids        |

*****Exceptions:
| **Sr. No.** | **Property**                        | **Metals (Exception)**                                             | **Non-Metals (Exception)**                                   |
| ----------- | ----------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------ | ------------------------------------------------------------ |
| 1           | **Appearance**                      | Some metals like **lead** and **tin** are dull                     | Some non-metals like **iodine** are shiny                    |
| 2           | **Malleability**                    | **Mercury** is a metal but liquid, not malleable                   | Some non-metals like **sulfur** can be molded slightly       |
| 3           | **Ductility**                       | **Mercury** cannot be drawn into wire                              | â€“                                                            |
| 4           | **Conductivity**                    | **Bismuth** and **lead** are poor conductors                       | **Graphite** (non-metal) conducts electricity                |
| 5           | **Density**                         | **Lithium**, **sodium**, **potassium** have low density            | â€“                                                            |
| 6           | **Melting & Boiling Point**         | **Mercury** melts at -39Â°C                                         | **Bromine** is liquid at room temperature                    |
| 7           | **State at Room Temp**              | **Mercury** is liquid                                              | **Bromine** is liquid; **oxygen** and **nitrogen** are gases |
| 8           | **Strength**                        | â€“                                                                  | **Diamond** (carbon) is extremely hard                       |
| 9           | **Reaction with Acids**             | Some metals like **gold** and **platinum** do not react with acids | â€“                                                            |
| 10          | **Tendency to Lose/Gain Electrons** | **Hydrogen** behaves like non-metal in some compounds              | â€“                                                            |

