**** Reactivity series:
Activity Series:

Potassium (K) > Sodium (Na) > Calcium (Ca) > Magnesium (Mg) > Aluminium (Al) > Zinc (Zn) > Iron (Fe) > Lead (Pb) > Copper (Cu) > Silver (Ag) > Gold (Au)
Key Points About Activity Series:

Most reactive metals (like K, Na, Ca) react vigorously with water and acids.

Moderately reactive metals (like Mg, Al, Zn, Fe) react slowly with acids and can displace less reactive metals from their salts.

Least reactive metals (like Cu, Ag, Au) do not react with water or acids under normal conditions.

Ag do not ract with oxygen in when heat and all:

**welding reaction:

1. Oxy-Acetylene Welding Reaction

The fuel used is acetylene (Câ‚‚Hâ‚‚) and oxygen (Oâ‚‚). The reaction produces a very hot flame (~3300Â°C) that melts the metal:

2ğ¶2ğ»2 +5ğ‘‚2 âŸ¶4ğ¶ğ‘‚2 +2ğ»2ğ‘‚ +heat2C2H2+5O2âŸ¶4CO2+2H2O+heat
Explanation:
Acetylene burns in oxygen â†’ produces COâ‚‚, Hâ‚‚O, and a very hot flame.
The hot flame melts the edges of the metal pieces.
A filler rod may be added to form a strong joint.
2. Electric Arc Welding
Uses electric current to generate heat.
No chemical reaction, just metal melts due to electrical energy.
Example: Iron pieces join when arc melts edges.

***Thermite reaction:
Fe2O3 + Al = Fe + AL2O3 +Fe+ heat:
The thermite reaction is a highly exothermic reaction used for welding, cutting metals, and producing very high temperatures.
Explanation:
Ferric oxide (Feâ‚‚Oâ‚ƒ) reacts with aluminium (Al) powder.
Aluminium reduces Feâ‚‚Oâ‚ƒ to iron (Fe).
The reaction produces aluminium oxide (Alâ‚‚Oâ‚ƒ) and a huge amount of heat (~2500Â°C).
The molten iron produced can be used for welding railway tracks, heavy machinery parts.
Key Points:
Itâ€™s an example of a redox reaction:
Aluminium â†’ oxidized (loses electrons)
Iron oxide â†’ reduced (gains electrons)
Requires ignition by magnesium ribbon or high heat because it doesnâ€™t start spontaneously.

